<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-275-270  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 275 270.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Feb 27 1989 v3 n9 p26(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Lights out: automated data centers promise greater productivity atlower cost.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wilson, Steve.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A new generation of systems software is appearing that automatesmany of the manual functions of the central data center.andP;  Fullyautomated data processing could significantly alter thetraditional roles of data center personnel by requiring theintervention of a human operator only in emergencies.andP;  Despite thepotential for lost jobs, however, industry analysts believe thenew data center will mean new roles for personnel.andP;  Analysts alsobelieve that successful automation depends more on managementskill than on technology.andP;  They urge managers to view theautomation process as a business decision that involves assessingthe impact of automation on the workforce.andP;  The analysts advisemanagers to involve employees in the shift to automation and tomake an effort to train them.andP;  Key areas targeted for automationinclude tape operations, console and report distribution.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Office AutomationCentralized Data BasesSystems SoftwarePersonnel ManagementJob SecurityPerformance-Cost RelationshipManagement of EDP.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>